00:28.778 --> 00:30.947
♪ From where I'm standing ♪

00:31.030 --> 00:34.659
♪ My grass is green. ♪

00:36.494 --> 00:41.416
♪ Someone once told me
the grass is much greener ♪

00:41.499 --> 00:42.625
♪ On the other side. ♪

00:42.709 --> 00:46.463
{\an8}Captioning sponsored by THE
U.S. DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION

00:46.546 --> 00:48.798
{\an8}and NICKELODEON

00:52.969 --> 00:54.304
{\an8}It's fine, it's fine.

00:54.387 --> 00:58.141
{\an8}It's just that, well, today
is the day Lucinda finds out

00:58.224 --> 01:00.643
{\an8}if Dirk is really
Clarice's father.

01:00.727 --> 01:02.312
{\an8}Even though
everybody knows

01:02.395 --> 01:02.937
{\an8}Dirk used to be
a woman

01:03.021 --> 01:05.147
{\an8}at the roller derby
circuit.

01:05.230 --> 01:07.192
{\an1}He'll be here soon,
I promise.

01:07.275 --> 01:09.611
Maybe Darren took
the bus home instead.

01:09.694 --> 01:11.488
{\an1}He asked me
to wait here, Dodie.

01:11.571 --> 01:13.782
{\an8}And we should, we should.

01:13.865 --> 01:15.325
{\an8}No question.

01:15.408 --> 01:18.161
{\an8}It's just <i> Our Loves, Our Lives</i>
starts in five minutes

01:18.244 --> 01:19.829
{\an8}and we haven't missed an episode
this whole year.

01:19.913 --> 01:23.124
{\an1}Then why don't you guys
go on without me?

01:23.208 --> 01:23.875
{\an8}Oh, wouldn't dream of it.

01:23.958 --> 01:26.795
{\an8}We BFFs stick together,
you know.

01:26.878 --> 01:28.379
{\an8}Four minutes, 43 seconds.

01:28.463 --> 01:29.714
{\an7}COURTNEY:
Ginger...

01:29.798 --> 01:30.882
{\an8}word is your birthday party
for Darren

01:30.965 --> 01:34.219
{\an8}is shaping up
to be the event of the year.

01:34.302 --> 01:35.345
Really?

01:35.428 --> 01:36.429
{\an1}You want
this party

01:36.513 --> 01:37.847
{\an1}to live up
to expectations.

01:37.931 --> 01:40.308
Or else no one
will ever come

01:40.391 --> 01:43.269
{\an1}to another one
of your parties again.

01:43.353 --> 01:45.522
Who wants that damage with
high school around the corner?

01:45.605 --> 01:47.440
Not me. Nope.

01:47.524 --> 01:47.899
Of course not.

01:47.982 --> 01:49.609
Say, "Bye, Ginger.

01:49.692 --> 01:51.236
See you at the party."

01:51.319 --> 01:52.237
What she said.

01:52.320 --> 01:53.947
We're working on it.

01:54.030 --> 01:56.282
Can we give you a lift?

01:56.366 --> 01:58.368
No, we're waiting for Darren.

01:58.451 --> 01:59.869
How cute--
waiting to walk home together.

01:59.953 --> 02:01.663
{\an1}Don't we need
to be somewhere?

02:01.746 --> 02:05.375
We're social creatures, Miranda.

02:05.458 --> 02:07.544
We need to be
in a lot of places.

02:07.627 --> 02:09.920
See you Sunday.

02:11.840 --> 02:13.925
{\an1}Hey... hey,
thanks for waiting.

02:14.008 --> 02:14.551
No thanks necessary.

02:14.634 --> 02:16.553
Sorry I'm late.

02:16.636 --> 02:17.762
Not nearly as sorry
as I'm going to be

02:17.846 --> 02:20.265
{\an1}if we miss
Lucinda's big news.

02:20.348 --> 02:21.766
{\an1}Come on!

02:26.396 --> 02:28.189
(<i> clears throat</i> )

02:28.273 --> 02:29.607
(<i> music starts playing</i> )

02:29.691 --> 02:32.569
♪ The sun is shining,
the spring is here ♪

02:32.652 --> 02:35.572
♪ It's a bunnyful time
of year ♪

02:35.655 --> 02:40.743
♪ Hoppity-hop,
it's an Easter bunny day ♪

02:40.827 --> 02:43.663
♪ My basket's filled
with chocolate creams ♪

02:43.746 --> 02:46.249
♪ Marshmallow chicks
and jelly beams ♪

02:46.332 --> 02:51.754
♪ Yummity-yum,
it's an Easter bunny day! ♪

02:51.838 --> 02:52.422
"Beams"?

02:52.505 --> 02:55.800
Did he just say "jelly <i> beams"?</i>

02:55.884 --> 02:56.801
Rhymes with "creams."

02:56.885 --> 03:00.305
There's no such thing
as a jelly <i> beam,</i> Carl.

03:00.388 --> 03:02.015
Besides, he's way
too over the top.

03:02.098 --> 03:05.810
We're going to lose out
on repeat business.

03:05.894 --> 03:06.936
That's okay.

03:07.020 --> 03:09.272
{\an1}We've got orders
coming out of our ears.

03:09.355 --> 03:11.274
{\an1}Hoods, we just may
have topped our own genius.

03:11.357 --> 03:15.069
{\an4}I mean, we're making
a fortune humiliating
Brandon Higsby

03:15.153 --> 03:18.531
{\an1}while selling
last year's Easter candy.

03:18.615 --> 03:19.407
Looky-looky-loo!

03:19.490 --> 03:22.452
{\an3}$17.

03:28.166 --> 03:29.292
{\an3}Well?

03:29.375 --> 03:30.126
Here.

03:30.209 --> 03:33.588
{\an1}Uh, next stop--
the Campbell residence.

03:33.671 --> 03:35.465
Whatever you say,
Carl.

03:35.548 --> 03:37.133
I can go all night.

03:37.216 --> 03:38.760
Higsby, you've got
to stop hamming it up.

03:38.843 --> 03:40.887
My mom says I'm showy.

03:40.970 --> 03:43.890
Well, we're looking for subtle.

03:43.973 --> 03:45.934
Showy has no place on Easter.

03:46.017 --> 03:49.103
Look, when you hire
Brandon Higsby,

03:49.187 --> 03:50.355
you get showy.

03:50.438 --> 03:50.772
You get flash.

03:50.855 --> 03:52.815
You get pizzazz.

03:52.899 --> 03:54.651
That's just how it is.

03:54.734 --> 03:56.527
Not anymore it's not.

03:56.611 --> 03:58.821
No one except my
tap-dance teacher

03:58.905 --> 04:01.407
tells me what to do!

04:01.491 --> 04:04.327
(<i> Brandon breathing heavily</i> )

04:04.410 --> 04:05.578
{\an3}I quit!

04:05.662 --> 04:06.829
{\an3}Huh!

04:09.374 --> 04:12.752
If you walk out that door, I'll
throw myself out that window.

04:12.835 --> 04:14.170
MAN (<i> on TV</i> ):
You have a daughter.

04:14.253 --> 04:15.505
WOMAN (<i> on TV</i> ):
So do you.

04:15.588 --> 04:17.423
MAN:
Good-bye, Lucinda.

04:17.507 --> 04:19.007
Happy birthday, Clarice.

04:19.091 --> 04:21.678
{\an5}LUCINDA:
Dearest Clarice,
when you grow up

04:21.761 --> 04:25.598
and your heart is broken like
it's never been broken before,

04:25.682 --> 04:29.686
you'll understand why your mommy
did what she's about to do now.

04:29.769 --> 04:32.480
Happy birthday, baby!

04:32.563 --> 04:33.481
(<i> shrieks</i> )

04:33.564 --> 04:35.525
(<i> glass shatters</i> )

04:35.608 --> 04:37.068
{\an5}Why didn't someone stop her?

04:37.151 --> 04:38.820
They just stood there
and watched her jump.

04:38.903 --> 04:40.822
{\an1}People on
soap operas

04:40.905 --> 04:42.865
have very slow
reaction times.

04:42.949 --> 04:45.535
Lucinda totally ruined
Clarice's party.

04:45.618 --> 04:46.494
Which just goes
to show you...

04:46.577 --> 04:49.664
That you should never
invite your mother?

04:49.747 --> 04:51.541
No, no, that you
have to consider

04:51.624 --> 04:52.917
every potential disaster,

04:53.001 --> 04:53.918
{\an1}including
maternal suicide,

04:54.002 --> 04:57.213
{\an1}whilst at the
party-planning stage,

04:57.296 --> 04:58.548
{\an1}which leads us
to Darren.

04:58.631 --> 05:00.883
I would never throw myself
out of a window,

05:00.967 --> 05:01.968
no matter how bad the party was.

05:02.051 --> 05:04.303
Darren,
Dodie is right.

05:04.387 --> 05:06.264
You need to go so we
can finish planning.

05:06.347 --> 05:09.767
Come on,
I'm still grieving for Lucinda.

05:09.851 --> 05:10.727
Darren...

05:10.810 --> 05:13.730
{\an5}Fine, but this
had better mean
that my party

05:13.813 --> 05:15.565
turns out better
than Clarice's.

05:15.648 --> 05:17.066
It will.

05:17.150 --> 05:17.525
That's a promise.

05:19.986 --> 05:22.822
Ginger, do you realize
that anyone that matters

05:22.905 --> 05:24.699
will be here
at your party?

05:24.782 --> 05:26.826
Not long ago a party
at the Foutley house

05:26.909 --> 05:29.746
wouldn't have even blipped
on the junior-high radar.

05:29.829 --> 05:32.248
A lot has changed, Macie.

05:32.331 --> 05:33.374
That's for sure.

05:33.458 --> 05:36.627
{\an5}And the BFFs have
been together
through it all--

05:36.711 --> 05:38.588
the good times
and the bad.

05:38.671 --> 05:39.922
Don't remind me.

05:40.006 --> 05:43.384
So, um, what do you guys think
I should do about party favors?

05:43.468 --> 05:46.763
Everyone needs to leave
with something memorable.

05:46.846 --> 05:48.431
How about
something springy?

05:48.514 --> 05:50.099
Oh, like live
bunny rabbits!

05:50.183 --> 05:52.602
{\an1}You might what to consider
the poop factor.

05:52.685 --> 05:53.603
{\an3}Ew!

05:53.686 --> 05:54.937
(<i> music playing</i> )

05:55.021 --> 05:56.439
♪ My basket's filled
with chocolate creams ♪

05:56.522 --> 05:59.984
♪ Whoa! Marshmallow chicks
and jelly beans ♪

06:00.068 --> 06:03.488
♪ Yummity-yum,
it's an Easter bunny day! ♪

06:03.571 --> 06:03.905
Yeah!

06:03.988 --> 06:08.201
Oh, how lovely!

06:08.284 --> 06:09.786
I'm telling you,
Carl,

06:09.869 --> 06:12.622
I think I could have
a future in karaoke.

06:12.705 --> 06:15.750
{\an1}Pal, you'll be able
to buy your own karaoke bar

06:15.833 --> 06:16.876
{\an1}before this weekend
is through.

06:16.959 --> 06:19.045
Hoodsey's Karaoke Den.

06:19.128 --> 06:22.799
Oh, man, Carl, I am
so all over that.

06:22.882 --> 06:24.884
{\an1}Come on, we've got
to score more candy.

06:24.967 --> 06:26.260
{\an1}LOIS:
Trust me, Ginger,

06:26.344 --> 06:28.763
{\an1}you could feed your guests
buffalo jerky

06:28.846 --> 06:31.224
and they'd still hoover
every last piece.

06:31.307 --> 06:33.476
The key is quantity
over quality.

06:33.559 --> 06:35.269
I say we put back
the cookie dough

06:35.353 --> 06:36.687
and make them
from scratch.

06:36.771 --> 06:39.232
{\an1}We can make twice as many
for the same price.

06:39.315 --> 06:41.359
Hmm! Now you're talking.

06:41.442 --> 06:44.278
{\an1}Meet you in
the soda aisle.

06:44.362 --> 06:46.572
CARL:
No one is going to notice

06:46.656 --> 06:48.783
that it's Halloween
clearance candy,

06:48.866 --> 06:52.495
and at 90% off, we're almost
doubling our per-unit profit.

06:52.578 --> 06:56.332
{\an5}HOODSEY (<i> on walkie-talkie</i> ):
But who's heard
of Easter vampires?

06:56.415 --> 06:58.501
(<i> both laugh</i> )

06:58.584 --> 07:00.169
{\an1}Carl,
what did I tell you

07:00.253 --> 07:02.171
about driving
to endanger?!

07:02.255 --> 07:02.839
I should've known.

07:02.922 --> 07:05.758
{\an1}Sorry about that,
JoAnn.

07:05.842 --> 07:07.468
Don't mention it,
Lois.

07:07.552 --> 07:08.386
{\an1}Whoa!

07:08.469 --> 07:10.930
I guess they had
a run on hams.

07:12.431 --> 07:13.266
{\an1}Excuse me.

07:13.349 --> 07:15.351
I believe I was
here first, Lois.

07:15.434 --> 07:18.771
We got here at exactly
the same time, JoAnn.

07:18.855 --> 07:22.275
I would have been here sooner,
but your son rammed my cart.

07:22.358 --> 07:25.153
LOIS:
Well, take that up with Carl.

07:25.236 --> 07:27.196
{\an4}Why don't you just
give up the ham
and call it a day?

07:27.280 --> 07:28.865
What part of
"This ham is mine"

07:28.948 --> 07:31.033
don't you
understand?

07:31.117 --> 07:31.742
The rude part!

07:31.826 --> 07:32.869
{\an1}(<i> gasps</i> )

07:32.952 --> 07:34.036
Ooh... ooh, my arm.

07:34.120 --> 07:36.372
Oh, I can't feel my arm!

07:36.455 --> 07:41.043
I'm... I'm having
crushing chest pain!

07:41.127 --> 07:42.128
(<i> gasping for breath</i> )

07:42.211 --> 07:45.798
Oh, that's low,
JoAnn--

07:45.882 --> 07:47.925
faking a heart attack
in the name of pork.

07:48.009 --> 07:52.346
{\an1}I... I...
I can't breathe.

07:52.430 --> 07:53.514
{\an1}(<i> gasps</i> )

07:53.598 --> 07:54.849
For the love of Peter!

07:54.932 --> 07:55.224
JoAnn?

07:55.308 --> 07:57.518
{\an1}(<i> gasps</i> )

07:57.602 --> 07:57.727
{\an1}Oh!

07:57.810 --> 08:00.521
Mom?

08:03.482 --> 08:06.944
{\an5}LOIS:
If I ever agree
to eat cockroaches

08:07.028 --> 08:09.363
while lying down
in a box of live snakes,

08:09.447 --> 08:12.116
I want you to lock me up
and throw away the key.

08:12.200 --> 08:12.909
Duly noted.

08:12.992 --> 08:15.077
Hello, everybody.

08:15.161 --> 08:16.996
Hi, Dave.

08:17.079 --> 08:18.414
Is my mom okay?

08:18.497 --> 08:19.123
Yes, uh, yes, indeed.

08:19.207 --> 08:22.418
{\an1}She'll be going home
momentarily.

08:22.501 --> 08:24.086
{\an1}Lois, may I have a word
with you?

08:24.170 --> 08:27.757
Nothing to worry
about, right?

08:27.840 --> 08:29.675
Well, I'm not sure.

08:29.759 --> 08:31.761
{\an1}There's good reason
to suspect a cardiac condition.

08:31.844 --> 08:35.765
{\an1}We're running some tests,
and until the lab work is back,

08:35.847 --> 08:37.600
{\an1}I've recommended she go home
and avoid any stress.

08:37.683 --> 08:41.604
{\an5}I'm telling you,
she is wound tighter
than a piano wire.

08:41.687 --> 08:43.356
How is she going
to avoid stress

08:43.438 --> 08:44.607
when she <i> is</i> stress?

08:44.690 --> 08:45.608
{\an1}JoANN:
I'll tell you how, Lois--

08:45.691 --> 08:50.404
{\an1}by eliminating the more
annoying aspects of my life,

08:50.488 --> 08:52.949
{\an1}namely the entire
Foutley family.

08:53.032 --> 08:54.492
That is
not fair.

08:54.575 --> 08:55.701
Listen here...

08:55.785 --> 08:57.328
Let a dying woman speak, Lois.

08:57.411 --> 09:00.289
{\an1}Dr. Dave has made it
clear to me

09:00.373 --> 09:03.167
{\an1}that stress could be
the cause of my condition,

09:03.251 --> 09:04.126
and like it or not,

09:04.210 --> 09:07.380
you and your family are
the cause of my stress.

09:07.463 --> 09:09.632
{\an1}So from now until
the end of my days,

09:09.715 --> 09:11.634
{\an1}I forbid--
and I repeat,<i> forbid--</i>

09:11.717 --> 09:13.970
{\an1}my family
from interacting

09:14.053 --> 09:15.846
with any member
of your family.

09:15.930 --> 09:18.724
What?! Whoa!

09:18.808 --> 09:21.811
{\an1}If I'm going to survive
this cruel world,

09:21.894 --> 09:25.481
{\an1}it's going to be
without a Foutley in my midst.

09:25.564 --> 09:26.399
Mom...

09:26.482 --> 09:28.484
{\an1}Not now,
Deirdre Hortense.

09:28.567 --> 09:29.318
{\an1}I'm sure you
and your brother

09:29.402 --> 09:32.029
will thank me for this someday.

09:32.113 --> 09:32.655
Come on.

09:35.074 --> 09:37.535
{\an5}GINGER:
<i>Here it is,</i>
<i>two days before I host</i>

09:37.618 --> 09:40.371
<i>the most important party</i>
<i>of my entire life,</i>

09:40.454 --> 09:43.082
<i>and one of my oldest friends</i>
<i>can't be there,</i>

09:43.165 --> 09:44.625
<i>which begs the question:</i>

09:44.709 --> 09:48.170
<i>Do I call off the party</i>
<i>or do I have it without Dodie?</i>

09:48.254 --> 09:50.172
{\an5}CARL:
This is Jelly Bean
calling for Cottontail.

09:50.256 --> 09:52.883
Come in, Cottontail. Over.

09:52.967 --> 09:56.345
{\an5}CARL (<i> on walkie-talkie</i> ):
This is Jelly Bean calling
for Cottontail.

09:56.429 --> 09:57.722
How do you read?

09:57.805 --> 09:59.515
What are you doing?

09:59.598 --> 10:02.184
Hoods, we have 17 baskets
to make by tomorrow morning.

10:02.268 --> 10:04.687
This isn't a good idea, Carl.

10:04.770 --> 10:07.523
My mom could go like that if she
knew I was even talking to you.

10:07.606 --> 10:09.817
CARL (<i> on walkie-talkie</i> ):
Your mom is faking it.

10:09.900 --> 10:10.776
I've seen that act
a hundred times.

10:10.860 --> 10:13.362
Now, I need your help
delivering these orders.

10:13.446 --> 10:16.324
Meet me here at my house
at 9:00 a.m.

10:16.407 --> 10:17.742
HOODSEY:
I can't risk it, Carl.

10:17.825 --> 10:18.701
{\an5}What do you mean?

10:18.784 --> 10:20.494
We have business obligations.

10:20.578 --> 10:21.370
She's my mother.

10:21.454 --> 10:23.372
I don't want to lose her, okay?

10:23.456 --> 10:25.708
{\an5}CARL:
But what about
Hoodsey's Karaoke Den?

10:25.791 --> 10:28.461
{\an5}HOODSEY:
That dream
will have to die, Carl.

10:28.544 --> 10:30.546
Oh! I didn't mean to say "die"!

10:30.629 --> 10:31.714
Never mind.

10:31.797 --> 10:32.923
Over and out.

10:34.467 --> 10:35.092
(<i> static crackling</i> )

10:35.176 --> 10:37.345
(<i> rustling</i> )

10:37.928 --> 10:40.389
Dodie, it's me,
Macie--

10:40.473 --> 10:42.016
Macie Lightfoot.

10:42.099 --> 10:43.684
Macie?

10:45.186 --> 10:47.146
{\an1}Macie, you're not banned
at my house.

10:47.229 --> 10:48.606
{\an1}You could use
the front door.

10:48.689 --> 10:51.233
{\an1}Oh, I guess I got caught up
in the drama.

10:51.317 --> 10:52.401
Tell me every detail.

10:52.485 --> 10:55.154
{\an1}I want to know
what everyone said

10:55.237 --> 10:57.114
{\an1}when they found out Ginger
was canceling the party.

10:57.198 --> 10:59.909
Um, Dode,
I'm not sure

10:59.992 --> 11:02.870
Ginger is planning
on canceling the party.

11:02.953 --> 11:05.247
What?!

11:05.331 --> 11:08.084
How could she consider
having that party without me?

11:08.167 --> 11:11.128
Well, technically
it is Darren's birthday party,

11:11.212 --> 11:12.755
and Darren is her boyfriend.

11:12.838 --> 11:14.340
{\an1}Well, yeah,
but this party

11:14.423 --> 11:16.425
{\an1}is also <i> the</i> most important
BFF thing to happen

11:16.509 --> 11:19.512
{\an1}since we got
to buy training bras.

11:19.595 --> 11:21.555
That was one
of my darker days.

11:21.639 --> 11:23.516
Macie Lightfoot, you tell Ginger

11:23.599 --> 11:26.352
that if she cared one iota
for our friendship,

11:26.435 --> 11:28.479
she would cancel this party!

11:30.022 --> 11:32.566
It's a miracle
you survived that fall, Lucinda.

11:32.650 --> 11:33.234
Hmm, uh-uh.

11:33.317 --> 11:35.152
Don't try to talk.

11:35.236 --> 11:36.654
{\an1}When those bandages
come off,

11:36.737 --> 11:38.280
{\an1}you'll be
as beautiful as ever.

11:38.364 --> 11:39.198
(<i> muffled moans</i> )

11:39.281 --> 11:41.659
{\an1}Oh, kiss me,
Lucinda.

11:41.742 --> 11:43.953
{\an1}Open that broken jaw
and kiss me.

11:44.036 --> 11:46.080
(<i> Lucinda moaning</i> )

11:46.163 --> 11:49.333
Oh, my goodness,

11:49.417 --> 11:51.794
I can't believe they show this
in the middle of the day.

11:51.877 --> 11:52.795
Here you go.

11:52.878 --> 11:54.088
That is skim milk, right?

11:54.171 --> 11:56.590
{\an1}I don't need any dairy fat
clogging my arteries.

11:56.674 --> 11:57.633
(<i> doorbell rings</i> )

11:57.716 --> 11:59.176
{\an1}Rest your arteries,
I'll get it.

11:59.260 --> 12:00.302
We're not buying

12:00.386 --> 12:03.013
{\an1}any more magazine
subscriptions.

12:03.097 --> 12:04.515
Okay.

12:06.350 --> 12:10.521
I'm looking for
a Hoods P. Bishop.

12:10.604 --> 12:12.815
Are you out
of your mind, Carl?

12:12.898 --> 12:14.525
I have a weak patient
in there.

12:14.608 --> 12:16.485
{\an1}Hoods, we stand to miss out
on some serious cake

12:16.569 --> 12:19.196
{\an1}if we don't deliver
those baskets.

12:19.280 --> 12:20.990
{\an1}We're sitting
on a gold mine.

12:21.073 --> 12:23.993
{\an1}Well, I'm sitting with
a heart-challenged mother

12:24.076 --> 12:25.494
{\an1}who says it's
because of you.

12:25.578 --> 12:27.413
Come on, Hoodsey.

12:27.496 --> 12:30.833
♪ Yummity-yum, it's
an Easter bunny day. ♪

12:30.916 --> 12:31.917
{\an1}No, Carl,

12:32.001 --> 12:33.335
she'll find out.

12:33.419 --> 12:34.462
{\an1}She can smell you
on me.

12:34.545 --> 12:37.131
{\an1}She's like a doberman
that way.

12:37.214 --> 12:40.009
So you're ending our friendship
over a fake heart attack?

12:40.092 --> 12:41.719
I guess so.

12:41.802 --> 12:45.264
Maybe it's time for you
to move on, okay?

12:45.347 --> 12:47.433
Don't call or write
or anything.

12:47.516 --> 12:50.519
It'll only
make it worse.

12:50.603 --> 12:51.562
Just forget I exist.

12:51.645 --> 12:55.691
{\an5}JoANN:
Robert Joseph, are
you burning toast?

12:55.774 --> 12:56.692
{\an1}Hey, Carl!

12:56.775 --> 13:00.112
{\an1}I told you I'd start
my own business.

13:00.196 --> 13:01.197
Want to hear our song?

13:01.280 --> 13:02.615
Beat it, Higsby.

13:02.698 --> 13:04.283
(<i> shrilly and off-key</i> ):
♪ Chick, chick, chick ♪

13:04.366 --> 13:05.618
♪ We're the Chickie Chicks ♪

13:05.701 --> 13:09.622
♪ And we got some treats
for you. ♪

13:11.207 --> 13:12.208
(<i> scoffs</i> )

13:12.291 --> 13:14.043
It doesn't even rhyme.

13:17.588 --> 13:18.714
GINGER:
<i>Courtney?</i>

13:18.797 --> 13:19.840
<i>It's Ginger.</i>

13:19.924 --> 13:21.884
COURTNEY (<i> on phone</i> ):
Hello, Ginger.

13:21.967 --> 13:24.887
We aren't playing childish games
at the party, right?

13:24.970 --> 13:26.722
Oh, no, of course not.

13:26.805 --> 13:27.556
But about the party.

13:27.640 --> 13:29.058
I need an unbiased opinion.

13:29.141 --> 13:31.060
Continue.

13:31.143 --> 13:32.728
Okay, well, Dodie's mom
and my mom had a fight

13:32.811 --> 13:35.856
{\an1}at the Bag-It-Yourself
Bargain Basement...

13:35.940 --> 13:37.566
Back story;
cut to the chase.

13:37.650 --> 13:38.567
Um, since then,

13:38.651 --> 13:40.986
her mom decided
that my family

13:41.070 --> 13:41.820
{\an1}is sort of
off limits to Dodie,

13:41.904 --> 13:44.740
{\an1}which means she can't
come to the party,

13:44.823 --> 13:45.991
{\an1}and she really
wanted to.

13:46.075 --> 13:47.076
{\an3}And?

13:47.159 --> 13:48.577
{\an1}And now that
she can't come,

13:48.661 --> 13:51.247
she wants me to call off
the whole thing, and...

13:51.330 --> 13:52.039
I don't know
if I should.

13:52.122 --> 13:54.583
Ginger, let me make this
crystal clear:

13:54.667 --> 13:56.293
It would be
a gigantic mistake

13:56.377 --> 13:58.087
{\an1}to cancel a party that
everyone is talking about.

13:58.170 --> 14:00.089
{\an1}I know.

14:00.172 --> 14:01.590
{\an1}But it feels disloyal
to have the party

14:01.674 --> 14:04.510
if my oldest friend
wants me to cancel.

14:04.593 --> 14:06.220
{\an1}And what if
I just postpone?

14:06.303 --> 14:07.429
Darren will understand.

14:07.513 --> 14:08.430
{\an3}Will he?

14:08.514 --> 14:09.848
On his birthday,
no less?

14:09.932 --> 14:11.475
Ginger... a girl must
never put the feelings

14:11.559 --> 14:14.436
of an overly
dramatic girlfriend

14:14.520 --> 14:17.147
{\an1}before the feelings of her
loving and doting boyfriend.

14:17.231 --> 14:19.275
People might talk.

14:19.358 --> 14:21.277
But it feels like
a stab at Dodie.

14:21.360 --> 14:22.736
Dodie's a big girl,
and she stabbed you

14:22.820 --> 14:26.323
in the back once before,
if my memory serves.

14:26.407 --> 14:27.449
{\an1}I guess.

14:27.533 --> 14:29.034
Aren't you glad
you called?

14:29.118 --> 14:30.786
Can't wait for
your party tomorrow.

14:30.869 --> 14:32.997
I'm all about
wide-leg palazzos

14:33.080 --> 14:34.164
with ruffled cuffs.

14:34.248 --> 14:35.249
Good to know.

14:35.332 --> 14:37.668
Thanks, Courtney.

14:37.751 --> 14:40.337
I can't believe the only party
I've ever thrown

14:40.421 --> 14:43.591
is turning out to be
such a gigantic disaster.

14:46.218 --> 14:47.886
{\an1}DARREN:
Hey!

14:49.096 --> 14:50.931
Hi.

14:51.015 --> 14:52.141
Thanks for
meeting me here.

14:52.224 --> 14:54.977
No problem-- but why
the coded directions?

14:55.060 --> 14:57.646
My mom's banned
your family, too.

14:57.730 --> 14:59.523
You're kind of
Ginger-adjacent.

14:59.607 --> 15:01.483
Darren, I need
to ask you a favor.

15:01.567 --> 15:02.151
{\an1}Shoot.

15:02.234 --> 15:04.320
Would you mind asking Ginger

15:04.403 --> 15:05.779
to cancel the party?

15:05.863 --> 15:07.448
Dodie, come on...

15:07.531 --> 15:08.574
She'll listen
to you.

15:08.657 --> 15:10.618
{\an1}Look-- Ginger
doesn't feel good

15:10.701 --> 15:12.328
{\an1}about having this party
without you,

15:12.411 --> 15:14.496
but it's my birthday

15:14.580 --> 15:16.874
{\an1}and she's excited
everybody's talking about it.

15:16.957 --> 15:17.625
{\an1}It doesn't seem fair
to cancel

15:17.708 --> 15:20.252
{\an1}because of
a war between mothers.

15:20.336 --> 15:21.670
I thought
you might say that.

15:21.754 --> 15:22.713
It would mean a lot
if you told Ginger

15:22.796 --> 15:25.591
it's okay with you
to have this party.

15:25.674 --> 15:27.760
But it's not okay
with me, Darren.

15:27.843 --> 15:29.053
In the old days,

15:29.136 --> 15:32.389
{\an1}Ginger would have never put
a party before her BFFs.

15:32.473 --> 15:34.850
But now that she has
a boyfriend,

15:34.933 --> 15:36.435
she doesn't care
anymore.

15:36.518 --> 15:37.686
Well, she does
so care, but...

15:37.770 --> 15:40.939
{\an4}If she cared,
she would call it off.

15:41.023 --> 15:42.358
{\an1}Hey, now, that's
totally one-sided, Dodie.

15:42.441 --> 15:44.360
You know, Darren,

15:44.443 --> 15:46.070
{\an1}you used to be
a much better friend

15:46.153 --> 15:48.447
before all this started
between you and Ginger.

15:48.530 --> 15:50.032
{\an1}You used to
actually listen,

15:50.115 --> 15:51.867
{\an1}and you didn't rush
to take sides.

15:51.950 --> 15:55.788
But now all you ever do is
defend Ginger-- no matter what!

15:55.871 --> 15:59.124
Ginger doesn't even
know I'm here.

15:59.208 --> 16:00.084
I came for you.

16:00.167 --> 16:02.336
You know, you say
Ginger doesn't care

16:02.419 --> 16:03.379
about the BFFs anymore.

16:03.462 --> 16:04.713
But what about you?

16:04.797 --> 16:07.216
You only care
about yourself--

16:07.299 --> 16:08.133
and you're
missing a <i> party!</i>

16:11.512 --> 16:13.597
Just forget
I said anything.

16:13.681 --> 16:14.556
Okay, Darren?

16:14.640 --> 16:16.016
Happy birthday.

16:18.143 --> 16:21.146
(<i> sobbing</i> )

16:21.230 --> 16:23.482
I could get used
to this lifestyle.

16:23.565 --> 16:24.775
I beats cleaning
bedpans.

16:24.858 --> 16:26.777
{\an1}Okay, the next house is
the Bouviers'.

16:26.860 --> 16:29.738
{\an1}You're going to have
to sing the song

16:29.822 --> 16:30.656
in French this time.

16:30.739 --> 16:33.409
Look, Carl, you'll get
one language out of me,

16:33.492 --> 16:34.159
that's it.

16:34.243 --> 16:36.912
Hoodsey would have
sung it in French.

16:36.995 --> 16:39.123
Hoodsey has more
panache than I do.

16:39.206 --> 16:39.581
(<i> brakes squeak</i> )

16:39.665 --> 16:41.625
Well, hello, Lois.

16:41.709 --> 16:43.919
I didn't know this was
your bunny trail.

16:44.002 --> 16:45.170
{\an1}Oh...

16:45.254 --> 16:46.296
Uh, well, hmm...

16:46.380 --> 16:49.049
{\an1}JoAnn Bishop's son was
Carl's business partner.

16:49.133 --> 16:50.092
Ah, yes, JoAnn.

16:50.175 --> 16:51.135
Uh...

16:51.218 --> 16:52.761
{\an1}I just got through
looking at her lab results.

16:52.845 --> 16:55.472
You were right--
her heart's just fine.

16:55.556 --> 16:58.392
It's an esophageal
hernia.

16:58.475 --> 16:59.727
I knew it!

16:59.810 --> 17:02.020
Come on,
we're taking a ride.

17:02.104 --> 17:04.606
You got to give JoAnn
this news right away--

17:04.690 --> 17:05.607
and I want to watch.

17:05.691 --> 17:08.609
With any luck she'll call off
this family feud

17:08.694 --> 17:11.280
and I can spare
whatever dignity I have left.

17:11.363 --> 17:13.240
But, Mom, you're
the Easter bunny.

17:13.323 --> 17:14.992
{\an1}You can't
just leave me.

17:15.075 --> 17:16.201
(<i> tires screech</i> )

17:19.038 --> 17:21.290
BRANDON:
♪ Chick, chick, chick ♪

17:21.373 --> 17:22.124
♪ We're the Chickie Chicks ♪

17:22.207 --> 17:27.546
{\an1}♪ And we got some treats
for you. ♪

17:27.628 --> 17:28.964
Hey, weren't
you working

17:29.048 --> 17:29.256
for Carl
and Hoodsey?

17:29.339 --> 17:31.049
Yep.

17:31.133 --> 17:31.967
{\an1}But our flair was
unwelcome,

17:32.050 --> 17:35.262
so Mr. Licorice and me
struck out on our own.

17:35.345 --> 17:37.139
Never can keep
a good chick down.

17:37.222 --> 17:38.974
That's for sure.

17:39.057 --> 17:41.852
Well, we have three more
deliveries to make.

17:41.935 --> 17:42.644
See you.

17:42.728 --> 17:44.438
♪ Chick, chick, chick ♪

17:44.521 --> 17:46.148
♪ The Chickie Chicks... ♪

17:57.076 --> 17:57.576
Are you mad,
girl?

17:57.659 --> 17:59.828
That's
salmonella city!

17:59.912 --> 18:02.664
Chill, Macie, it's
one piece of dough.

18:02.748 --> 18:04.750
Sorry, I lost my head.

18:04.833 --> 18:05.959
I'm just a little off

18:06.043 --> 18:06.919
with all this conflict
in the air.

18:07.002 --> 18:09.505
But you're doing
the right thing

18:09.588 --> 18:10.756
by having the party,
Ginger.

18:10.839 --> 18:13.634
Ugh... that's what
everybody says.

18:13.717 --> 18:16.929
But why doesn't that make me
feel any better?

18:17.012 --> 18:18.889
Ginger! Macie!

18:18.972 --> 18:19.932
{\an3}Darren!

18:20.015 --> 18:20.849
{\an1}What's up?

18:20.933 --> 18:22.017
You won't believe

18:22.100 --> 18:24.520
the idea I got from
a kid in a chicken suit.

18:24.603 --> 18:26.980
Courtney advised us
against party games, Darren.

18:27.064 --> 18:27.898
No, no, no, no,
look, look, look.

18:27.981 --> 18:29.900
There are two ways
to face a problem:

18:29.983 --> 18:33.153
You either throw in the towel
and give up

18:33.237 --> 18:35.197
like Lucinda did
when Dirk left her

18:35.280 --> 18:36.532
or you dust yourself off

18:36.615 --> 18:38.075
{\an1}and face your problem
head on

18:38.158 --> 18:39.493
like the singing chick did

18:39.576 --> 18:40.369
{\an1}when he started
his own business.

18:40.452 --> 18:42.120
Yeah...

18:42.204 --> 18:43.372
Well, don't you get it?

18:43.455 --> 18:44.832
If we want Dodie to be here
for the party,

18:44.915 --> 18:47.543
{\an1}it's up to us
to make it happen.

18:47.626 --> 18:50.128
{\an5}You mean defy
Mrs. Bishop's
demands?

18:50.212 --> 18:51.421
If that's
what it takes.

18:51.505 --> 18:52.214
No, Darren,

18:52.297 --> 18:55.425
{\an1}Mrs. Bishop is
a very unstable lady.

18:55.509 --> 18:59.137
I know... which is why
we may have to do this

18:59.221 --> 19:01.056
secret-agent style.

19:10.566 --> 19:12.276
{\an1}(<i> whispering</i> ):
You go first.

19:13.694 --> 19:16.572
(<i> grunts</i> )

19:16.655 --> 19:19.366
(<i> sobbing</i> )

19:22.119 --> 19:23.161
Oh... oh...

19:23.245 --> 19:24.746
(<i> shrieking</i> )

19:24.830 --> 19:26.331
(<i> thudding, moaning</i> )

19:27.541 --> 19:28.750
Oh, hi, Dode.

19:28.834 --> 19:30.919
{\an1}Ginger?

19:31.003 --> 19:33.172
{\an4}Aren't you
getting ready
for your party?

19:33.255 --> 19:34.047
{\an3}I am.

19:34.131 --> 19:35.549
What are you
doing here?

19:35.632 --> 19:37.301
I'm not having it
without you.

19:37.384 --> 19:38.594
We're here
to bust you out.

19:38.677 --> 19:39.761
{\an1}(<i> gasps</i> )

19:39.845 --> 19:40.554
Oh, Ginger!

19:40.637 --> 19:41.430
(<i> moaning</i> )

19:41.513 --> 19:44.433
We're stuck.

19:44.516 --> 19:47.853
{\an1}But we're going to need
another escape route.

19:52.107 --> 19:53.984
If it weren't
for the floppy ears,

19:54.067 --> 19:56.612
{\an1}I'm sure my blood pressure
would soar right now.

19:56.695 --> 19:57.779
(<i> laughs</i> )

19:57.863 --> 20:00.782
Hey, good one,
Mrs. Foutley.

20:00.866 --> 20:02.784
{\an1}JoAnn, I've looked over
the results of your tests--

20:02.868 --> 20:04.786
your heart is fine.

20:04.870 --> 20:06.580
{\an1}What you're
suffering from is

20:06.663 --> 20:07.956
{\an1}an overactive
bile duct.

20:08.040 --> 20:10.459
{\an1}Nothing a sensible diet
won't keep in check.

20:10.542 --> 20:11.668
Really?

20:11.752 --> 20:14.421
Well... well,
isn't that good news?

20:14.504 --> 20:15.631
Oh, I'm so relieved!

20:15.714 --> 20:20.802
Look, I'm sorry if a little
tug of war caused you any harm,

20:20.886 --> 20:22.638
and as far as my family
causing you stress,

20:22.721 --> 20:24.932
I'm sorry for that, too.

20:25.015 --> 20:26.016
JoAnn, you don't
have to like me,

20:26.099 --> 20:29.144
but you can't go on
stopping our kids

20:29.227 --> 20:29.728
from having fun together.

20:29.811 --> 20:32.648
Face it, they're a posse.

20:32.731 --> 20:36.318
Well, I... I guess I overreacted
in the face of death.

20:36.401 --> 20:40.364
I... I don't know what came
over me in that supermarket.

20:40.447 --> 20:43.867
{\an5}And as far as
my condemnation of
your family goes,

20:43.951 --> 20:46.536
I suspect it
isn't always Carl

20:46.620 --> 20:47.871
at the head of trouble.

20:47.955 --> 20:49.498
I know my Robert Joseph has

20:49.581 --> 20:51.250
a touch of the devil
in him, too.

20:51.333 --> 20:53.043
And I don't have
a single reason

20:53.126 --> 20:55.504
to fault Ginger
in any of this.

20:55.587 --> 20:57.589
{\an1}So you'll let Dodie come
to the big shindig tonight?

20:57.673 --> 20:59.841
We're serving ham.

20:59.925 --> 21:02.469
I-I don't see why not.

21:02.552 --> 21:03.345
Deirdre Hortense!

21:03.428 --> 21:04.930
You'd better get
a move on

21:05.013 --> 21:07.015
if you want to get
to Ginger's party!

21:07.099 --> 21:07.891
(<i> panting</i> ):
Thanks, Mom!

21:07.975 --> 21:10.394
{\an6}GINGER:
Come on,
hurry.

21:10.477 --> 21:11.853
Hallelujah!

21:11.937 --> 21:15.524
Don't forget the ears!

21:15.607 --> 21:18.068
Look, we had every intention
of delivering,

21:18.151 --> 21:19.778
but my Easter bunny...
went into labor.

21:19.861 --> 21:21.989
(<i> doorbell rings</i> )

21:22.072 --> 21:23.657
You know how
rabbits are.

21:23.740 --> 21:26.576
♪<i> Le soleil brille,</i>
<i>le printemps est là</i> ♪

21:26.660 --> 21:29.538
♪<i> C'est un bon jour</i>
<i>pour les lapins...</i> ♪

21:29.621 --> 21:32.582
{\an1}<i>Mon ami,</i> our bunny
is back in business.

21:32.666 --> 21:35.877
See you in 20.

21:35.961 --> 21:38.755
(<i> rock music playing</i> )

21:40.424 --> 21:43.343
GINGER:
<i>The party was a huge hit.</i>

21:43.427 --> 21:46.138
<i>If spring is a time</i>
<i>for making a fresh start,</i>

21:46.221 --> 21:50.142
<i>then this party may have just</i>
<i>been the perfect spring event.</i>

21:50.225 --> 21:52.561
{\an1}How long have you
known the cool girl

21:52.644 --> 21:53.937
{\an1}who's throwing
the party?

21:54.021 --> 21:55.731
Oh, we've been
best friends

21:55.814 --> 21:57.232
since, like,
second grade.

21:57.315 --> 21:58.191
Cool!

21:58.275 --> 21:59.609
Is that her boyfriend?

21:59.693 --> 22:00.902
Yeah, that's
Darren.

22:00.986 --> 22:04.072
He's only, like,
the coolest guy I know.

22:04.156 --> 22:05.741
At least that
I know so far.

22:05.824 --> 22:08.994
Oh, this ham bone will
make a delicious soup.

22:09.077 --> 22:11.288
Not part of your
new diet, Jo-Jo.

22:11.371 --> 22:14.082
Besides, I already
promised it to Carl.

22:14.166 --> 22:17.294
He's starting a jewelry business
and wants it for a pendant.

22:17.377 --> 22:17.669
You do indulge the boy.

22:17.753 --> 22:19.880
Hmm.

22:19.963 --> 22:21.423
Pass the olives.

22:21.506 --> 22:24.593
{\an5}GINGER:
<i>It was a night</i>
<i>of new beginnings--</i>

22:24.676 --> 22:26.845
<i>a new understanding</i>
<i>between our moms,</i>

22:26.928 --> 22:28.263
<i>a new popularity for me</i>

22:28.346 --> 22:30.891
<i>as the cool girl</i>
<i>who's throwing the party,</i>

22:30.974 --> 22:33.602
<i>and a new realization</i>
<i>for Dodie, Macie and I</i>

22:33.685 --> 22:37.314
<i>that if we're going from being</i>
<i>BFFs to BFFs with boyfriends,</i>

22:37.397 --> 22:39.983
<i>it was going to take</i>
<i>a little extra effort</i>

22:40.067 --> 22:42.444
<i>to make sure nothing</i>
<i>came between us.</i>

22:52.037 --> 22:54.831
{\an8}and NICKELODEON

22:54.915 --> 22:58.335
{\an8}Captioned by
Media Access Group at WGBH
access.wgbh.org

23:29.616 --> 23:32.410
{\an8}JoANN:
Robert Joseph,
are you burning toast?
